I agree.  IP source addresses for authentication is a dangerous practice.
Two things make it necessary.

We run 4.xBSD networking software and it relies on this
practice heavily.

If you remember to take this authentication with a grain of salt,
and only REALLY rely on LOCAL IP addresses being "authentic", then
you can probably get by. This practice becomes a powerful convenience.
Within a local organization, you can really depend
on the address-&gt;name mapping to be reliable, and this is where it
is very convenient to do authentication.

You've got to draw the line somewhere, and many people draw that line
too far from "home".

					Kirk

